Lessons learned while architecting scalable React component design systems

11 min read
Just now

--

Press enter or click to view image in full size

Honestly, I never set out to become the “go-to” design systems engineer. I come from product-led work, and the design systems side started out of curiosity — a way to bring more value to the engineering teams I was working with. I still wouldn’t call myself an expert. But over the last two years I’ve been the lead design system engineer and owner at two very different companies.
The first was an early-stage startup: two product teams of around six people each, all feeding into a single dashboard product. The second was a mature organisation with five product teams of roughly nine people each, every team owning a separate consumer-facing project.
Neither was starting from scratch. In both cases the design system already existed — an orphaned codebase nobody owned, contributed to ad hoc whenever someone needed a component and had a spare afternoon. That turned out to matter more than the size difference.
What surprised me was how similar each organisation’s problems were. Different sizes, different maturity, near-identical pain points. This post is a quick look back at top 4 lessons I learned about what works and what doesn’t. I hope you find it useful, I did my best keeping it short.
TLDR;

• Lesson 1 — Get the foundations right first — pick what you’re standing on before you write a component

• Lesson 2 — Use JSX slots, not config props — composition beats configuration

• Lesson 3 — Don’t build from scratch — headless UI exists for exactly this

• Lesson 4 — Ship test drivers — so your refactors don’t break everyone’s test suite

• Lesson 5 — Gatekeep early — someone has to say no, and it has to happen before design handoff

Lesson 1 — Get the foundations right before anything else
A design system exists to help teams build consistent UI faster. Everything downstream — velocity, adoption, the quality of your components — depends on decisions you make in the first few weeks. Get these wrong and you spend the next two years fighting them. I did.
Decide what you’re building on
The first question isn’t “what components do we need.” It’s “what are we standing on?” Broadly, three options: build from scratch (please don’t — more on that later), customise a pre-made system like Material UI, or build on a headless foundation like Radix UI or React Aria.
The way I’d frame the choice: how much does your product need to look like itself?
If your UI doesn’t need to differentiate stylistically — internal tooling, dashboards, admin panels — reach for something styled that works out of the box. Override the theme configuration and move on.
There’s a benefit here I didn’t appreciate until I’d lived without it: you inherit the library’s documentation, and it’s usually excellent. You only have to document your overrides. That’s a maintenance burden you never take on.
But spot the gaps early. There will always be a component the library doesn’t cover: charts, an unusual autocomplete, a date picker. Decide how you’ll handle those before you commit, not six months in.
What you want to avoid is picking a turnkey system and then constantly fighting its API and design philosophy every time you need a customisation.
If your product has strong branding and custom UI needs, and the goal is not to look like another Material UI theme, use a foundation that leaves styling out. Radix and Adobe’s React Aria both do this well — you get behaviour and accessibility, you bring the visual identity.
You won’t cover everything with one tool
You’ll be missing a component or two. That’s normal and fine. As long as the team agrees on a primary foundation, adding a specialised outlier library — say, something like downshift dedicated to complex dropdowns — is reasonable. That’s still not building from scratch; you’re borrowing someone else’s solved problem, just from a second source.
What I’d watch is the compatibility layer you write to bridge them. If your system is built on Tailwind, pulling in a Material UI component means a compatibility layer that will make you miserable.
Then get your styling system down
Once the tool is picked, the styling foundations come next:

• Spacing scale — one base unit, 4px or 8px. Everything derives from it.

• Type scale — sizes, line heights, weights. Fewer steps than you think.

• Colour — a semantic layer over primitives (bg-surface, text-muted), never raw hex in components. Build dark mode into the token structure from day one, even if you don't ship it.

• Radii, borders, shadows — small, fixed sets.
I put this second for a reason. Whatever tool you picked will have a documented way to customise it, and following that path saves you from fighting the library later.
💡 Top Tip — Check for a Figma starter
Before your designer builds anything, have them check whether the system you chose has either official or a community-maintained Figma kit. I’ve seen designers spend weeks rebuilding a system foundation from scratch when a configurable template for that exact library already exists.
