Lesson 2 — Create composable component APIs with JSX slots
I’ll keep this one short because the idea is simple and the code makes the argument better than I can.
In every codebase I’ve worked in, component API design came down to two approaches: configuration-based and slot-based. If you’re aiming for composition, I’d go with slots every time.
A configuration-based API:
type CardProps = {
title: string;
subtitle?: string;
icon?: IconName;
iconPosition?: 'left' | 'right';
actionLabel?: string;
onAction?: () => void;
badge?: string;
badgeVariant?: 'success' | 'warning';
};<Card
title="Deployment"
subtitle="Last run 2h ago"
icon="rocket"
actionLabel="Redeploy"
onAction={redeploy}
badge="Live"
badgeVariant="success"
/>
This works fine until someone needs something you didn’t anticipate. Two actions? A link instead of a button? A tooltip on the badge?
Each one is a new prop, a new ticket on your board, and another branch in a component that’s slowly turning into a configuration language.
A slot-based API:
type CardProps = {
header?: ReactNode;
media?: ReactNode;
children: ReactNode;
footer?: ReactNode;
};function Card({ header, media, children, footer }: CardProps) {
return (
<div className="card">
{header && <div className="card__header">{header}</div>}
{media && <div className="card__media">{media}</div>}
<div className="card__body">{children}</div>
{footer && <div className="card__footer">{footer}</div>}
</div>
);
}
<Card
header={
<>
<Icon name="rocket" />
<h3>Deployment</h3>
<Badge variant="success">Live</Badge>
</>
}
footer={
<>
<Button onClick={redeploy}>Redeploy</Button>
<Link href="/logs">View logs</Link>
</>
}
>
Last run 2h ago
</Card>
What I like about this: the card owns layout, spacing and structure, and the consumer owns content. Two actions, a link, a tooltip — none of those need you at all now.
Simple idea, but I kept seeing teams default to a configuration API for no particular reason. It’s more tedious to maintain and more tedious to use. React composition comes through more naturally with slots, so that’s where I’d start.
Lesson 3 — Don’t build from scratch
I hinted at this earlier, and it’s the one I’d push back on hardest: I have yet to see a case where building components from scratch turned out to be the right call.
The core problem, as far as I can tell, is that engineers without design system exposure wildly underestimate what a seemingly “simple” component takes to build and own. I’ve watched the temptation show up in two situations — when a team hits customisation friction with an existing library, and when they’re starting a system from scratch and the blank page looks appealing.
In my opinion, teams talk themselves into it two ways: unfamiliarity with the alternatives, usually meaning they don’t know what the starter solutions can do or how far customisation can go — and a belief that their UI needs are unique, usually paired with a fear that using a starter will look templated.
And here’s what I’ve watched teams underestimate:

• The cost is invisible up front. The initial component build is roughly 10% of the work. Accessibility, edge cases, testing, documentation, versioning, migration paths and ongoing support are the other 90% — and they never end. You simply don’t know what you don’t know.

• Bus factor. Two people build it and understand the internals. Both leave. Now what? The components are frozen, the documentation is stale or was never written, and everyone else is reverse-engineering it. Nobody knows why things work the way they work, and it’s too costly to change.

• You’ll rebuild a worse version of Radix or Material UI anyway. Those teams have spent years on edge cases you haven’t thought of yet — keyboard navigation, focus trapping, screen reader announcements, RTL, touch targets — and they’ve documented all of it.
Personally, I’m a fan of headless UI precisely for the cases people think justify building from scratch. If the objection is “we need our own visual identity,” headless gives you exactly that — Radix and React Aria hand you behaviour and accessibility and leave the styling entirely to you.
The unique thing about your UI is almost never the interaction model of a dropdown. It’s the CSS.
Here’s a decent video explaining the headless UI concept you can check out;
I have yet to come across a case where building from scratch was justified and worked out well. I’d genuinely like to see one, though — if you disagree, make your argument in the comments. 🙏
Lesson 4— Ship test drivers
This one I didn’t see coming, and it turned out to be one of the highest-leverage things I shipped.
As a design system matures, component internals change. Structure gets refactored, APIs evolve, a dropdown gets rebuilt to fix an accessibility bug. That’s expected and healthy.
What isn’t obvious until it happens to you is the blast radius. A product team upgrades the design system to pick up a fix in one component, and their test suite lights up red — hundreds of failures, none of them related to what they wanted.
I thought I was safe because I hadn’t touched the surface API. But I’d done something just as bad: I restructured the JSX of a dropdown, and every test that traversed that markup was now broken.
Do this to a product team once and it’s an annoyance. Do it regularly and you will have people who don’t like you.
The FIX— ship an abstraction layer for tests
A test driver is a thin layer the design system owns and exports, sitting between consumer tests and component internals. Consumers query through the driver instead of reaching into the DOM themselves.
Here’s a super simplified example of the idea:
// design-system/testing/dropdown-driver.js
export const dropdownDriver = (screen) => ({
open: async () => {
await userEvent.click(screen.getByRole('combobox'));
},
selectOption: async (label) => {
await userEvent.click(screen.getByRole('option', { name: label }));
},
getSelectedValue: () =>
screen.getByRole('combobox').textContent,
});And now, your consumer projects can use the abstraction:
// consumer app test
const dropdown = dropdownDriver(screen);
await dropdown.open();
await dropdown.selectOption('Vilnius');
expect(dropdown.getSelectedValue()).toBe('Vilnius');You can restructure the JSX however you like. As long as the driver’s API stays stable and you update its internals alongside the component, nothing breaks downstream. The contract moves from markup shape to behaviour, which is what those tests were trying to assert in the first place.
The tradeoff
This only works if consumer projects share tooling and stay on compatible major versions. If one team is on Enzyme and another on React Testing Library, you’re maintaining a separate wrapper per setup — a dark forest I never ventured into.
